Border restrictions extended another month.
same as last forecast

The recent change in CDC protocols and the accelerated pullback on mandates across the world makes me hesitate now. The timeline is short, but a discretionary permit finding its way into the next update seems more plausible today.

It would be a very bad symbolic gesture if the rest of Canadians cannot traveled, so maybe he is confident himself that a lot of Canadians will be vaccinated at this time.
To stop this covid first step is to have 70 % or more vaccinated , then entry for all tested , healed or vaccined. Only in 2022 ..2023 no more restrictions.
It's a long shot, but there's a slight possibility vaccinated travelers will be allowed to travel to Canada from the US later this month.

The vaccination procurement and distribution in Canada has not been particularly successful, but supply chains and cross border flows have remained intact which has allowed Canadian authorities to be in less of a hurry to lift the restrictions. The current restrictions, reviewed on a monthly basis are currently in force until April 21. Biden has asked for all states to be prepared to make all its people eligible to access vaccinations by May 1st. According to the CDC it takes at least two weeks for a covid vaccination to become effective which suggests June 1 being too early to lift restrictions.
Adjusting to after June 1
Reducing probability of this happening before 1st June as there is unlikely to be enough time for a vaccine passport system to be set up

All airline passengers to the United States ages two years and older must provide a negative COVID-19 viral test taken within three calendar days of travel. Alternatively, travelers to the U.S. may provide documentation from a licensed health care provider of having recovered from COVID-19 in the 90 days preceding travel.
The current surge in Canada is going to prevent further re-openings, especially risky ones like international travel.
It is expected that most Canadians will be vaccinated by end of June, not before
Updating from 0/0/0/20/80 as we are just 2 months away from the top bucket and I doubt that's enough time to set up any kind of vaccine passport system.

Canada will require proof of vaccination. A formal system needs putting in place. It takes time to do that, and won't happen within the next two months. However, discretionary relaxation would be possible and might be quickly put in place at the border.
Adjusting to after June 1
Canada has smart people running the country.
Cases are increasing again in Canada in what could be the start of a third wave. It will take some time to bring it back under control. Reducing to zero probability for prior to 1 June.

Not enough is going to change before June 1. There's so much coronavirus spread in the US, and barely a majority of the US population has some level of immunity to the virus. I think they'll expect that people willing to travel might be less likely to be vaccinated as well. And then they're having their own problems with virus spread, too. I think they'll wait. By July 1, probably. But it's not clear to me that vaccine certificates could be implemented in the next 5 weeks. I would think they would give people some notice before any such change took effect, too. Could they make such changes effective on May 21? Building on the excellent analysis of @Mark_T and following the certainty expressed in the latest forecast from @SE_Meyer, whom I have learned to ignore at peril to my Brier score, I am moving up my estimate to 100% “not before June 1.” As of March 5, Canada has fully vaccinated just 1.5% of their population.[1] Canada’s problems with getting enough vaccine have meant they need to draw on their COVAX allotment, even though that means taking vaccine meant for poor countries and will still have only 8 million doses by the end of March.[2] The unreliability of supply has caused the government to continue with its September timeline for “delivering vaccines to all Canadians who want them.” Even if you believe they are underpromsing to overdeliver, this is not a country that is going to welcome discretionary visitors from the U.S. before June 1.
Adjusting towards long term... I could also see the USA holding the border closed depemding on Canada's ability to vaccinate.
Updated based on vaccine announcements from US and Canadian governments.

Vaccination rates in Canada continue to lag USA. Politics of travel during COVID-19 pandemic in Canada also continue to support the current approach to the US border until conditions change on both sides of the border. Difficult to see how this will be true before summer 2021 at the earliest.

Forecast based on an assumption that the Canadian government will be looking for reasons to open up the lucrative tourism trade from the US when conditions (infection rates and vaccination roll outs) can be seen as "balanced" / close to in parity across both countries.

Decreasing Feb-March and increasing the later two buckets. No news on this that I can see and probably still depends on relative cases. Likely still a month or two before this current wave has ended and cases have dropped significantly in the US.

I note the question concerns foreign nationals entering Canada from the US rather than just US citizens/residents. I am assuming this is about border controls only. The issue here is the disparity between the Canadian and US health systems. Canada has a universal health system based on need rather ability to pay. As we are aware the US system is State based, private and based on the ability to pay. A universal system is considered as a part of a socialist doctrine which is an anathema to Americans. This has created an inability to handle the pandemic in the US as opposed to the Canadian model. The Canadians do not want to overwhelm their hospital system with importing further problems from the US, where the pandemic is out of control. Vaccinations will take at leats until the second quarter to have an effect.

Hypothesis: Discretionary travel depend of success of vaccine program AND individual health certificate (certified negative test) not available fast enough. 1- Many pressures from Quebec to close borders; 2- More vaccines coming in spring; 3- Numbers from United States very, and sadly, very high. 4- New Administration in Washington, and decentralize health system (States, Cities and private sectors).

Political scandals related to discretionary travel over the Holidays makes this decision more complex. Continued worsening of COVID-19 in both countries will slow the timeline and pending arrival of new US Administration is something to watch in the coming weeks.

The roll-out of the vaccine in the U.S. is going slower than expected even though the U.S. has bought a huge amount of the available and expected production of vaccines. The roll-out in Canada is going well, timely, but they have a different priority list than many U.S. states. They are vaccinating older people more than the U.S. is currently, which means the general population is farther down the priority list. So U.S. general pop. still constitutes a sizable risk group for Canadian gen. pop. Est. timeline for U.S. gen. pop. to get vaccine is end of summer 2021 now, so I think Canada will push opening borders for leisure travel until late summer 2021 at least. If roll-out in U.S. picks up speed that timeline may shift back to May timeframe again. Canada benefits economically from travel by U.S. gen. pop.

Not more than 115 000 vaccines dose have been delivered in Quebec, most affected by the covid-19. 115 000 / 8 000 000 !... There is pressures from Ottawa, and pharma to give double dose, so there is less than 1% of the population that get vaccine.

However, giving rising numbers in both countries, it appears unlikely the talks will move quickly. There is also falling confidence among Canadians about permitting U.S. travel. We are likely looking at a Q2 or later decision.

There is no reason to risk it for low demand. Discretionary travel would likely go to primarily Toronto and Montreal, highly dense areas where the virus is more likely to spread.

I think this really depends on when vaccination begins to take effect - once enough people are vaccinated, the infection rates should start to drop exponentially. Allowing for logistics of distribution, I guess we might be at 50% vaccination sometime around March, give or take a month. Also assuming some people will maintain some social distancing even with the vaccine, this should put r0 below 1 some time in this time frame. At that point it's a question of how fast the curve drops off and how much political will there is to reopen borders.

I think travel could be somewhat restricted to those with proof of vaccination, depending on how well the vaccines are doing. But, of course, that depends on how quickly the vaccines roll out. I'm thinking they will come very quickly once Trump Administration is out of office, and someone who understands the logistical complexities is running the distribution. Anyway, on this question, I'm leaning a little into hope.
Vaccines can make the daily count of new cases drop very fast. I am expecting the daily new cases in US to drop below 25k by January end
Updating for "what if some vaccine certificates" are around

Considering how public health officials have managed this situation thus far, the decision would be made based on the status of the outbreak. Travel restrictions were one of the first measures taken, and rolling them back has never been seriously discussed at any point since they started in March, leading me to believe that the outbreak will have to be at a very low and stable level before the restriction is lifted. The restriction has been renewed every 30 days on the 21st of the month without much fuss. I also focus on the US, since the decision to allow Americans into Canada will rest more on the status of our outbreak, which has been consistently worse anyways.

Rising US positivity and indifferent federal effort does not encourage change. Even federal change in January only affects federal effort and many states will continue with minimal effective measures. If things turn for the better, Canada will still wait to insure low general positivity to suppress new introductions.
Cases situation in both countries means that only last two bins viable. My answer would be different if last bin was 1st of August.

Current virus trends will not change until their is a change in leadership January 20th. But the virus will be completely out of control by then and will require months to get under control. Best case would be April, worst case?
i think with the arrival of vaccines, maybe "widely" by late Q1 2021, and maybe "Covid Passports" or the like, "discretionary" (conditional) could start being possible soon thereafter..
The current uptick in US infections requires me to adjust the forecast to push the date further into the future.
It definitely won't happen before the inauguration in January. There will be a stronger federal Covid task force and a vaccine on the way.
Canada has covid under better control than the US and there is large popular support for keeping the border closed, Until the US gets covid under control, the border will stay closed.
Not till the wave of infection falls locally and globally

Unless a New President is elected on November 3, the current administration's stated approach of letting the virus run its course and to spend time and money on treatments and the vaccine instead will be seen as crazy by most of the world. Canada as the nearest neighbor is the canary to the US stupidity.

By end of Q1, Covid will be an endemic rather than a pandemic, so it will already have spread to Canada regardless of any preventative measures, so closing the border is a punitive measure that will only serve to spite Trump. Additionally, the emergence of vaccines will mean that although stopping covid is no longer possible, it will be less significant than it is today. Therefore Canada will be able to make some political gains by opening the border and giving Biden an easy way (thus repudiating the legacy of the Trump administration) whereas there will be no political gains to be made from keeping the border closed past that point, and quite a lot of economic damage.

The true answer depends on 1. the state of Covid 19 in the US and 2. whether Biden or Trump win the US presidential election. The current stats for US Covid 19 and predictions by Dr Fauci et al show no great improvement in infections before the Spring of 2021 so the border will remain closed. If Biden is elected there is more likely to be a significant push to reduce infection numbers and improve public health actions to limit spread. From a strictly Canadian point of view there is absolutely no hurry to open the border for more than essential goods and services.

Canadians don’t appear to want this currently and their populist prime minister is very eager to appease (reducing scrutiny on his own scandals). Until cases go down/vaccine available, not happening.

Both Canada and the US are experiencing a spike in the Covid-19 infection rate, the US more so. The Canadian health care system appears to be more successful than the US in handling the pandemic given the numbers per 100,000; to open the border would increase the risk for an increase of infections. There is no advantage for Canada to open its borders to non-essential travel from the US and later rather than sooner is probably wise. This could be the second wave of the pandemic, high spike with less deaths due to the increased knowledge of the virus, but there is a potential for four diminishing waves given historical data with a total period of two years (Spanish Flu 1918-1920) and the virus is approximately 11 months old (including the early Chinese experience). Assuming the release of drugs and the possibility of a vaccine in the new year, the first possible date of opening borders would be 1st/2nd Quarter 2021.
